The Chronicles of Aetheria: An Age of Shattered Splendor
Historians mark the beginning of recorded time as the Year of the First Quill, 10,000 Before the Shattering (B.S.). Before this, the world of Aetheria existed in myth and oral legend—fragmented tales of gods walking among mortals, primordial spirits shaping the land, ancient great dragons flying the skys and the First Races awakening from the dreams of the World Tree. It was only when the unified elven scholars of Sylvandar, the human runescribes of the nascent Empire of Valoria, and the deep-delving chroniclers of the dwarven Holds of Karadun together created the High Aetheric Script that true history could be preserved.
The Golden Age (10,000 – 9,000 B.S.)
For one thousand glorious years, Aetheria knew unparalleled prosperity. This era is now remembered as the Golden Age of Magic, or simply the Ascendancy.
The great continental powers rose almost simultaneously:

The Empire of Valoria, a vast human realm that spanned the fertile heartlands.
The Eternal Sylvandari Dominion, the ancient elven forest-kingdoms whose living cities grew from the very trees.
The Deep Kingdom of Karadun, a dwarven empire of mountain-spanning halls and forge-cities.
The Beastkin Clans of the Great Savannahs and the Floating Republics of the Azure Isles, ruled by merfolk and avian folk.
Scattered but powerful dragon-pacts, where Ancient Great Dragons (beings born in the dawn of time) served as living gods, teachers, and sometimes tyrants to lesser races.

Magic was not merely a tool—it was the lifeblood of civilization. Arcane academies floated above clouds, ley-line forges powered automatons of living crystal, and life-weavers extended lifespans to centuries. Spells that could raise mountains, heal entire armies, or open gates to distant planes were commonplace among the gifted. Artifacts of unimaginable power were crafted: the Crown of Eternal Dawn, the Singing Blades of the Thousandfold Song, and the Dragonheart Reservoirs that stored raw mana.
Economy, philosophy, architecture, and warfare reached their zenith. Flying cities drifted between continents. Great Dragons taught forbidden lore to chosen apprentices. Professions now lost to time— Artificery, Golem/Automaton construction,Astral Architects, Soul Forgers, Chronomancers, and Void Singers—shaped reality itself. It was an age of wonders, hubris, and ever-growing ambition.

The First Great War and the Shattering (Year 0 – The Cataclysm)
No single event triggered the end. Scholars argue that it was the inevitable result of centuries of escalating rivalries, the exhaustion of easily accessible mana veins, the apathy of silent Gods ,  and the jealousy mortals felt toward the Ancient Great Dragons who hoarded the deepest secrets of magic.
In 9,000 B.S., the world burned.
The war lasted decades but felt eternal. Alliances shattered and reformed in blood. Human legions marched alongside elven spell-singers against dwarven rune-golems. Beastkin hordes clashed with merfolk navies and everything in between. Worst of all, the Dragon Schism saw the Ancient Great Dragons turn upon one another and upon the mortal races they once guided. Their battles scarred continents—entire mountain ranges were vaporized, oceans boiled, and reality itself tore in places.
Tens of millions perished. Whole civilizations were erased. The floating cities plummeted. The ley-line network fractured, causing magic storms that still rage in certain blighted regions. Most of the high arts were lost as masters died with their secrets. The greatest dragons fell; their colossal bones became landmarks and sources of residual power. Entire professions vanished overnight. The High Aetheric Script itself became unreadable to all but a handful of survivors, its linguistic and magical keys destroyed.
When the ashes settled, the world was broken. Borders were meaningless. Empires collapsed into petty kingdoms. The Age of Strife had begun.

The Long Night: 9,000 Years of Blood and Chaos (0 – Present)
For nine millennia, Aetheria knew almost no true peace. The constant low-level warfare is so normalized that many cultures simply call the current era the Eternal War or the Red Centuries.
Humans warred with humans over fertile valleys and ruined arcane ruins. Elven houses fractured along philosophical lines—purists versus those who would mingle with shorter-lived races. Dwarven clans fought endless feuds over collapsing mines and ancestral grudges. Beastkin tribes splintered into predator and prey factions. Even demons turned upon themselves in the hellish realms.
Into this chaos came the Infernal Incursion.
Taking advantage of the shattered world, the Demon Lords and Devil Princes of the lower planes launched coordinated invasions across every continent roughly 8,700 years ago. Their legions poured through weakened planar rifts. Demonic hordes—monstrous amalgamations of fang, scale, chitin, and corrupted flesh—carved out massive territories. Some demons resemble nightmarish beasts or living siege engines. Others, the rarer Highbloods, appear nearly human: pale or obsidian skin, glowing red or violet eyes, horns, tails, or bat-like wings (most famously the succubi and incubi lineages). These Highbloods often serve as generals, diplomats, or seducers, wielding both raw power and cunning intellect.
Over the centuries, demonic realms such as the Bloodsworn Dominion in the east, the Obsidian Theocracy in the south, and the Abyssal Marches in the north became entrenched powers. Countless wars were fought to contain or expel them, yet they remain. Many mortal kingdoms now border—or are even vassals to—demonic territories, leading to tense truces, forbidden trade in soul-shards and hellsteel, and hybrid bloodlines that some call "tainted" and others "blessed with strength."
Borders have shifted endlessly. Ancient Valoria is now 15 squabbling successor Kingdoms and a dozen poor grand duchies. The Sylvandari Dominion splintered into the High Forest Enclaves and the savage Wildwood Exiles. Karadun’s halls are divided among rival thanedoms. New powers have risen: the Iron League of merchant-princes, the Dragon Cult Remnants who worship the bones of fallen Ancient Great Dragons, and the Veiled Republic, a shadowy alliance of mages who hoard the little rediscovered lore.

Today, the world remains medieval in technology and society, yet scarred by ancient wonders. Ruined floating citadels loom on the horizon. Dragon bones form the foundations of some cities. Demonic incursions still threaten remote regions. Petty kings, archmages, warlords, and demon princes vie for power while adventurers delve into live magical dungeons that offer rewards (drops) of all kinds items— forgotten ruins seeking the glories and the dangers—of the lost Golden Age.

The Fragility of Memory and the Written Word
Though history books, imperial chronicles, temple scrolls, enchanted memory crystals, and dwarven stone tablets have survived from many eras, true knowledge of the distant past remains elusive. The High Aetheric Script and its regional variants used during the Golden Age and the early centuries after the Shattering are indecipherable to nearly all living scholars. Only in the last 300 to 400 years have linguists, aided by rare artifacts and the painstaking work of polyglot sages, begun to translate texts from roughly the last four centuries with any reliability. Everything older remains locked behind linguistic and magical barriers that have yet to fall.
Even the long-lived elves, whose eldest can remember events from over two thousand years past, have lost direct access to the oldest knowledge. One thousand years ago, a mysterious event known only as the Veiling struck the elven enclaves. In a single night, vast numbers of elder elves suffered a collective erasure of ancient memories. Entire libraries of personal recollection vanished from their minds, and many of the most powerful archdruids and loremasters were left as shells of their former selves. Some whisper it was a curse from a dying Ancient Dragon, others blame a failed ritual or a demonic incursion that targeted the immortal races specifically. Whatever the cause, even the elves now rely on the same fragmented, recently translated texts as the shorter-lived races.

The Dragons: Ancient and Modern
The Ancient Great Dragons were primordial beings who existed since the first dawn of Aetheria, predating even the recorded eras. They were not merely powerful creatures but living embodiments of elemental and cosmic forces—teachers, tyrants, and architects of reality. Their deaths during the Great War and Shattering marked the true end of the Golden Age.
Their lesser descendants, simply called Great Dragons, still inhabit the world. Born after the Cataclysm, these dragons are pale shadows of their ancestors in both size and power. They are few in number but not vanishingly rare; new dragons are born every few centuries. Most choose to remain hidden in remote mountain peaks, deep caverns, or floating sky-isles, emerging only rarely. Sightings are so uncommon that many common folk dismiss them as mere legends or exaggerated tales told by adventurers. Those who have seen one often describe them as majestic yet melancholy creatures, aware of the faded glory their kind once possessed.
Some unverified reports suggest that dragons lay their egg(s) deep in mountains and ancient mines. When they are born, for the first 3 years, these babys are extremely dangerous killing anything that comes close the their home nest (The Red Rage). There they grow for two hundred years and break open the mountain/mine rock to leave their nest. Already after their inicial rage fase, dragons demonstrate high intellect, communication through telepathy before they lean how to speak the common tongue.

The Rise and Fall of the Vel'thorne Empire
Amid the endless wars of the Age of Strife, moments of unity occasionally emerged.
Approximately 2,800 years ago, the human lands were forged into a single mighty realm: the Vel'thorne Empire. Through conquest, diplomacy, marriage alliances, and the visionary leadership of Emperor Vaelor the Unifier, nearly the entire human continent came under one banner for the first time since the Shattering. The empire’s golden banners flew from the southern coasts to the northern frostlands.
For roughly 800 years, Vel’thorne devoted much of its strength to reclaiming territories lost to the demonic invasions. Great crusades pushed the infernal forces back, reclaiming ruined cities and shattered ley-lines. At its height, the empire stood as the strongest mortal power since the Golden Age.
Then, two thousand years ago, disaster struck. After centuries of grinding warfare, the Demon Lords coordinated a devastating multi-front assault. Several key defensive lines collapsed simultaneously. Demonic legions marched on the imperial capital of Thalor Vael. The city was sacked in a week of unimaginable horror. Emperor Vaelor XIII was slain, the imperial family scattered or killed, and the empire shattered overnight.
In the aftermath of victory, the demons and devils turned upon each other as they always do. Rival Demon Lords and Hell Princes fought brutal civil wars for control of the newly conquered lands. Because of this infighting, they lost the vast majority of the territory they had gained. What took mortals centuries to reclaim was squandered by the victors in mere decades.

The Eternal Sylvandari Dominion (Golden Age)
In the ancient days before the Shattering, the elves were the closest of all mortal races to the primordial harmony of the world. They called their realm the Eternal Sylvandari Dominion — not a single empire of stone and banners, but a vast, living network of forest-kingdoms, sky groves, and moonlit crystal cities grown rather than built.
Their greatest cities — Luminara, Thalassel, Elyndor, and the capital Sylvandar itself — were living wonders. Trees taller than mountains formed spiraling palaces, rivers sang with enchanted currents, and the very leaves shimmered with woven starlight. The elves of this era were near-immortal, with many living for five thousand years or more. They were the greatest masters of Nature, Spirit, and Life magic the world had ever seen, working in close harmony with the Ancient Great Dragons and the World Tree.
Elven society was ruled by the High Star Council, a gathering of archdruids, moon-singers, and star-seers. They viewed themselves as stewards of the world rather than its rulers. For a thousand years they stood at the pinnacle of the Golden Age alongside Valoria and Karadun.
The Fall and the Long Fracturing
Like all great powers, the Sylvandari Dominion was shattered during the Great War. Many of their living cities were burned, corrupted, or torn from the land. Countless ancient bloodlines were extinguished. In the nine millennia that followed, the elves never again achieved true unity.
They fractured into dozens of enclaves, kin-bands, and exiled factions. Two major branches eventually emerged and still define elven identity today:

The High Forest Enclaves (also called the Silverleaf Realms)
The more “civilized” and isolationist descendants. They control the largest remaining ancient forests in the central and western continents. Their cities are still grown from colossal trees, protected by living barriers of thorn and song. They maintain strict traditions, revere the old ways (as much as they can remember them), and generally look down upon the shorter-lived races. Magic is more common among them than in humans, and they produce a higher percentage of Nature and Spirit mages.
The Wildwood Exiles (also known as the Bloodthorn Tribes or Savage Sylvari)
Descendants of those who rejected the High Council’s retreat into isolation. They live deep in the most dangerous, monster-haunted wilds and corrupted forests. Many have embraced primal, almost feral lifestyles. Some clans have even made uneasy pacts with dark spirits or minor demons. They are far more open to outsiders (especially those who prove their strength) but are also significantly more violent and unpredictable.

The Veiling – 1,000 Years Ago
One thousand years ago, the greatest blow to elven knowledge occurred. During a grand conclave meant to reunite the major enclaves, a mysterious cataclysm known as the Veiling swept across elvenkind. In one night, the oldest and most powerful elves suffered total erasure of their ancient memories. Millennia of accumulated personal wisdom, magical insights, and historical recollection vanished. Many archdruids and lore-wardens were left catatonic or childlike.
To this day, no one knows the true cause. Some blame a dying Ancient Great Dragon’s final curse. Others suspect demonic interference, a betrayed god, or a failed attempt to restore lost Golden Age magic on a massive scale. Whatever the truth, even the longest-lived elves now struggle with the same fragmented history as humans. The Veiling is considered the true end of whatever remained of elven supremacy.

The Deep Kingdom of Karadun (Golden Age)
During the Golden Age, the dwarves stood as the unbreakable backbone of Aetheria. Their realm was known as the Deep Kingdom of Karadun, a continent-spanning empire of mountain roots and subterranean wonders. Unlike surface empires, Karadun was never a single nation above ground — it was a vast network of interconnected holds, grand halls, and forge-cities carved deep into the bones of the world.
Their greatest achievements included:

Karad-Dur, the eternal capital-city beneath the Worldspine Mountains, whose halls could house millions.
The Living Forges powered by captured lava veins and Aetherite crystals.
The legendary Sky-Piercing Holds — mountain fortresses so tall their peaks touched the clouds.

Dwarven mastery of rune magic, Aetherforge techniques, and engineering was unmatched. They constructed automatons of living stone and metal, built underground highways that spanned continents, and crafted artifacts capable of withstanding the fury of Ancient Great Dragons. Dwarves of this era often lived for 600 to 900 years, their bodies and minds hardened by the stone they revered. They saw themselves as the eternal craftsmen of the world, partners to the dragons in shaping reality itself.
The Fall and the Long Fracturing
The Great War struck Karadun with catastrophic force. Surface mountains were shattered, underground seas boiled, and entire holds were buried under collapsing stone. Many of the greatest forges went dark as ley-lines ruptured. The loss of master runesmiths and Aetherforge secrets during the Shattering was a blow from which they have never fully recovered.
In the 9,000 years that followed, the once-mighty Deep Kingdom fractured into independent Great Holds, Clan Confederacies, and isolated Deep Delves. Some clans turned inward, sealing their gates and becoming xenophobic. Others became wandering guilds of master craftsmen, selling their unmatched metalwork and engineering skill to any who could afford it. A few darker clans fell to greed, delving too deep and awakening ancient horrors.
The Forging of the Black Anvil – 1,700 Years Ago
Seventeen centuries ago, a cataclysmic event known as the Forging of the Black Anvil nearly broke dwarven civilization. A massive incursion of demons and underground aberrations (possibly awakened by reckless deep-delving) assaulted the major holds simultaneously. In a desperate ritual, the High Runelords of Karad-Dur sacrificed a vast amount of their ancestral knowledge and living stone itself to create the Black Anvil — a legendary artifact said to be capable of reforging reality.
The ritual succeeded in driving back the invaders, but at terrible cost. Countless master runes were burned from existence, and many of the eldest dwarves suffered permanent mental scarring similar to the elven Veiling. To this day, the Black Anvil remains sealed in the deepest vault of Karad-Dur, its exact powers and location known only to the Stone Council.

The Clans of the Great Savannahs and Wild Realms (Golden Age)
In the Golden Age, the Beastkin — also called Beastfolk or Beastmen — were among the most vibrant and free civilizations of Aetheria. They dominated the vast Great Savannahs, primal rainforests, towering mountain valleys, and untamed wildlands. Unlike the rigid empires of humans, elves, or dwarves, they were never a single unified nation. Instead, they formed the Great Beastkin Pact, a vast alliance of tribal confederations bound by blood oaths, spirit pacts, and the will of the Ancient Great Dragons.
Each clan was tied to a specific animal totem (Lion, Wolf, Eagle, Serpent, Bear, Panther, etc.), granting them distinct physical traits, instincts, and innate abilities. Their cities were living masterpieces — great tree-villages, cliff-carved strongholds, and mobile tent-cities that followed the great herds. Beastkin shamans and totemic druids worked powerful Nature and Spirit magic, often enhanced by their own bestial blood. Many could partially or fully transform, blending humanoid intellect with raw animal power.
At their peak, the Beastkin were respected (and sometimes feared) equals to the Sylvandari Dominion and Karadun. Ancient Great Dragons frequently chose Beastkin as companions and champions, drawn to their primal honesty and fighting spirit.
The Fall and the Great Sundering
The Shattering hit the Beastkin harder than most. Their open lands offered no natural fortresses against dragonfire and arcane cataclysms. Entire clans were wiped out, sacred migration routes were destroyed, and many totemic spirits died or went mad. The Great Beastkin Pact shattered into countless warring tribes.
In the 9,000 years since, Beastkin have fought each other as fiercely as they fought outsiders — predator clans against prey clans, old blood feuds, and territorial disputes over scarce resources in a broken world. Many tribes devolved into nomadic raiders or isolated hunter-gatherers, while others adapted by carving out kingdoms in fertile river valleys or dense jungles.
The Blood Moon Calling – 2,400 Years Ago
Approximately 2,400 years ago, a powerful spiritual event known as the Blood Moon Calling swept across all Beastkin. For one full lunar cycle, every Beastkin felt an overwhelming primal urge. Many tribes united under charismatic warlords and launched massive campaigns to reclaim ancient savannah heartlands. Some scholars believe this was the world’s lingering magic trying to restore balance. Others claim it was the final howl of a dying Ancient Great Dragon.
The unification was temporary. After several decades of conquest and glory, old rivalries reignited. The alliance fractured violently, leaving behind even deeper grudges. The event is still celebrated in festivals and mourned in dirges to this day. Many Beastkin shamans believe another Blood Moon Calling is approaching — an omen that could either unite their people once more or doom them to final extinction.
